ads.author: Rob LaDue
ads.title: Black Rose Pinball Machine - Pirate Themed
ads.description: Gorgeous Black Rose Pinball Machine -Pirate Themed This beautiful Black Rose, pirate-themed, pinball machine was produced in 1992 and features many unique game elements, including a pop-up twisting cannon shot to sink ships and shoot bonus shots, video-mode bonus games (uses the flippers to play a Knife Throwing, Walk-the-Plank, and Swing-from-the-Rigging analog video game), Easter-egg bonuses for trick shots, treasure bonuses, parrot bonus, etc. Play is flawless! All plastics and metals are in great condition, and the lights, cannon, analog display, 3 flippers, plunger, sound, and ball eject perform perfectly. Complete Operations Manual included. This machine has been lovingly used for home play since our purchase of it in 2008. We are a smoke free home. At the time of purchase, the machine had been completely shopped, including replacing many of the older incandescent lighting with LEDs. Some of the incandescent lights were retained to provide some of that old school pinball feel. All rubbers were replaced last year, a pinball specialist gave it a once over in December 2024, and the field was recently rewaxed. The cabinet and playfield are near flawless and the legs are free of rust. Before being returned to the States for its reshop in 2007, this machine was exported to Italy. It retains its original Italian lire coin return buttons. The game speaks and displays English (go figure!). The coin change box was missing when we acquired it, but is easily found on the internet. For an older (and more affordable) pinball game, Black Rose has so-ooo many different and unique elements and shots, that our family never got tired of it (our moving necessitates the sale). The pirate theme is exciting for both adults and children too and for those that desire, the game can be upgraded with the Skull and Bones kit, which changes the game in many interesting ways. Please message me with any questions and I will do the best I can to answer them. Play tests can also be arranged (located in Bradenton, FL). Shipping must be arranged by the buyer. Beautiful machine! Thanks!

ads.description: Incredibly rare piece. It’s been displayed as art with me for several years. Time for it to move on to new adventures. Asking $125 obo It was produced by Stern Electronics, Inc. in June 1980. The machine was designed by Joe Joos Jr., with the distinctive art by Doug Watson. Only 1,201 units were produced, making it a relatively rare and sought-after title among pinball enthusiasts. The backglass artwork is noted to be inspired by the cover of the July 1978 issue of Heavy Metal magazine, attributed to artist Philippe Cazaumayou.

ads.author: Brian Marks
ads.title: 1978 Bally KISS Pinball Machine - Signed by Peter, Gene, Ace & Paul
ads.description: I have a 1978 Bally KISS pinball machine autographed by all 4 original KISS band members. Peter, Gene, Ace, and Paul. They signed the plastic playfield pieces. The serial number on the machine is EKI1022, which means it's number 22 out of 17,000 produced. Visit this link to see the serial number formats - http://www.ipsnd.net/details.aspx?id=50128 The 22nd KISS pinball machine ever produced by Bally comes with some unique features because of how early on it was made in production. The arrows on the playfield are different colors on both sides of the letters KISS, but later on, they decided to use all one color, orange-ish, red. More on that here under the "Game Traits" tab - "KISS Card Arrow Inserts" - http://www.ipsnd.net/view.aspx?id=1386 There are only two other machines produced earlier than the one I am selling that are registered on the internet pinball serial number database. The serial numbers on the head of the machine match the body. Here is a link to this machine on the internet pinball serial number database - https://www.ipsnd.net/details.aspx?id=50128 Everything on the machine works and it's absolutely beautiful to look at. I upgraded the scoreboards to LED ones so I could enjoy the machine being on, and not ruin the originals scoreboards. I kept the original scoreboards, and they still work. I upgraded the motherboard to preserve the original one. I kept the original motherboard, and it works. All the bulbs on the machine were upgraded to LED so I could enjoy the machine illuminated ambiance without worry of the bulbs getting hot. I also kept all the original bulbs, and they still work. I have the original manual for the machine. The pinball machine comes with rollers which make it super easy to move. Asking $20,000 Please let me know if you would like to see more photos.

ads.author: Kevin Coughlin
ads.title: 1968 Bally Dogies Ultra Rare EM Pinball Machine
ads.description: Very clean and well preserved 1968 Bally Dogies Pinball Machine. Works well, has new rubber and ball (not pictured) game plays fast and fun! The playfield and backglass are in very nice condition, the cabinet has original paint that is flaking and yellowed with age which is usual for the games from this era Bally DOGIES was designed in August 1967 and manufactured in several Production-Runs from January to September 1968. The Machine is without any Doubt one of the absolute Masterpieces as well from Ted Zale as from Jerry K Kelley. Artist Jerry K Kelley told in a Conversation from 2000 that he and Designer Ted Zale had a very good Relationship and both of them liked the Idea for a Machine with a Rawhide-Theme featuring Dogies thundering through Canyons. It was a very successful Machine and ranked as the 2nd-best-selling Bally until 1972. As usual with Bally from 1964 to 1972 there were Models in english or german Language available. This one is English! Sadly, like each Bally-Machine from late'66 to late'68, it suffers from flaking Cabinet-Colors. This wasn't due to bad/cheap Quality but due to a chemical Process. It became evident when the first Machines showed that Effect after 2 years, in late '68 (the first ones were BAZAAR and CAPERSVILLE). Bally immediately reacted. Newer Machines like COSMOS did not suffer anymore. At least half of the 3,670 Units went to Germany where it was very popular and is still easy to find there. Very sad is the Fact that, while many Americans would love to own a DOGIES, still some of them get converted by european V-Pin-Clowns. Important Terms of Sale – Please Read Carefully This pinball machine is being sold AS-IS, WHERE-IS with NO WARRANTY EXPRESSED OR IMPLIED. The game has been fully described to the best of my ability and is in working order at the time it leaves my shop. Once the machine leaves my possession, I am not responsible for any issues, damage, adjustments, or failures that may occur during shipping, transport, setup, or ownership. No returns. No refunds. No exchanges. Pinball machines are complex electromechanical devices and may require routine maintenance, adjustments, or minor repairs after transport. Buyer assumes all responsibility once the machine is picked up or shipped. By purchasing this item, the buyer acknowledges and agrees that they have reviewed all photos, read the description in full, and understand the nature of buying a used pinball machine.

ads.author: Kevin Coughlin
ads.title: 1979 Williams Gorgar Pinball Machine
ads.description: 1979 Williams Gorgar pinball machine in very good condition, all original boards all in very nice condition and working and playing perfectly, no battery damage to board but will need a new battery holder installed or NVRam to save settings and high scores, I haven't done it.. just have to turn it in and off and on again real quick to boot it up.. doesn't bother me.. backglass is an 8 out of 10 with minimal wear and flaking, the original scoreboards all work, sometimes players 3-4 take a little while to warm up, sound and speech is perfect and awesome! Playfield is a 9 out of 10, very minimal wear, same with cabinet art, game has been cleaned and shopped and had leds added to GI and backbox, incandescent bulbs in all playfield lights.. I been playing it for last year and I need space back in my shop, time for it to find a new home! I also have added white carrot flippers to it ... all new rubbers and ball, waxed and cleaned and ready to rock! Gorgar was the first talking pinball machine with a vocabulary of seven words: Gorgar, Speaks, Beat, You, Me, Hurt, Got. The words could be combined together for different phrases. This may sound rather ridiculous 40 years later but was absolutely leading edge in 1979, not only for the pinball-industry but for technology in general, and nobody should forget that. Plus, after the sensational success of FLASH, it was the second SS-milestone for Williams and did a further important step to beat Bally and becoming #1 in the industry. It still ranks at #15 of the most produced Flippergames ever. Important Terms of Sale – Please Read Carefully This pinball machine is being sold AS-IS, WHERE-IS with NO WARRANTY EXPRESSED OR IMPLIED. The game has been fully described to the best of my ability and is in working order at the time it leaves my shop. Once the machine leaves my possession, I am not responsible for any issues, damage, adjustments, or failures that may occur during shipping, transport, setup, or ownership. No returns. No refunds. No exchanges. Pinball machines are complex electromechanical devices and may require routine maintenance, adjustments, or minor repairs after transport. ads.author: Russel Benthal
ads.title: All Original 1981 Nintendo Donkey Kong Arcade Machine TKG4-UP-US
ads.description: This is an all original, complete, working example of 1981 Nintendo Donkey Kong arcade machine in original cabinet. Recently acquired from an estate near Ballantyne. Currently at a storage facility in Pineville, NC - right beside Carolina Place Mall. This is an extremely rare piece of vintage American history. The "holy grail" to many collectors and enthusiast. Every single piece of the machine is original, other than the fluorescent light bulb for the marquee, which i replaced with a brand new Feit bulb from Home Depot yesterday. Original CPU board, video board, transformer, power supply, wiring harnesses, original Sanyo monitor, monitor board, coin mechanisms, and even the original graphics! Zero modifications to the unit, other than the previous owner bypassed the coin mechanisms to allow free gameplay (this can easily be reversed). Yes, it does work. The unit powers on, plays music, lights up, and you can see the picture on the screen in color. The picture does need to be adjusted with some sort of plastic tool which I do not have. Pickup only, or I can arrange delivery after payment has been made. Cash, Cashapp, or Paypal. I will also take trades on gold & silver, mens watches, electronics, tools, and collectibles. I look forward to speaking with you soon.

ads.author: Allen Robinson
ads.title: Pole Position, Upright Arcade, Atari/Namco 1982
ads.description: Vintage Upright Arcade – Pole Position (Atari/Namco, November 1982) Price: $475, Negotiable (but not by much) Step into racing history with this original Pole Position upright cabinet — one of the most iconic arcade racers ever made. Released in 1982 by Atari/Namco, Pole Position was a groundbreaking driving simulator that set the standard for racing games. It’s widely recognized as one of the Top 50 most historically important video games of all time. Condition: - Cabinet is very old and needs some love. - Boards need work and likely new caps. - Monitor does not power on. - Lights come on. - No sound currently. - This is a project cabinet — perfect for restoration enthusiasts or collectors. Highlights: - Classic upright racer with simulator-style gameplay. - Rare piece of arcade history from the golden age. - Great candidate for restoration or display in a collection. Important: - Price is negotiable, but only slightly. - Sold as-is. - Serious buyers only.

The monitor probably has fewer than 200 hours on it since it was constructed. The sides are new, smooth black laminate. ads.author: Chck Falcon
ads.title: Atari Centipede Cocktail Sit Down Arcade Cabinet (Fully Serviced and Playing Great!)
ads.description: Hi there! Up for sale is a nice vintage Atari Centipede Cocktail Arcade Cabinet from 1981. What a classic! Centipede is one if my fave arcade games. I think the cocktail cabinet version is even cooler. In a 2 player game, once a player dies, the whole screen flips to the direction of player 2, and vice versa! The game is fully working and playing beautifully. The monitor, the logic PCB, the audio/power regulator, and power supply boards have all been rebuilt/recapped with high quality Nichicon electrolytic capacitors. Afterward each board was recalibrated to operate at factory spec voltages. Both track balls were also rebuilt, so the track ball glides smooth and easy all over the playfield. The monitor and all the boards have been cleaned and the inside was vacuumed, making this a clean machine inside and out. Perfect for your game room, your business, your bar, etc. Everyone loves this game. This machine has been dialed in to work well for years and years to come. I know the new owner will be very happy. Feel free to email me with any questions that you may have.

It’s a rare find that captures the excitement of 90s arcade culture. ads.author: Adrian Melendez
ads.title: Non-Marring Playfield Stands (Black) - Free US Shipping
ads.description: If you work on your own pinball machines, these make shop work easier, safer, and way less annoying. These are purpose-built playfield stands designed by pinball repair and restoration folks to securely support a playfield above the cabinet while you work. They hold the playfield stable without resting it on cabinet rails or forcing you to lean into the machine. Printed in durable TPU (rubber-like material), not hard plastic. That means they’re tough, slightly flexible, and won’t chip, crack, or damage your cabinet or playfield edges if bumped. Why these are better than rigid stands or improvised supports: Non-marring TPU material protects cabinet rails and playfield edges Slight flex absorbs bumps instead of transferring impact Stable enough for modern playfields with ramps, upper PFs, and heavy wiring No slipping, no scratching, no stress on the cabinet Way more comfortable access for shop outs and repairs Great for: Full shop jobs and cleanings Switch and mech work Rubber swaps and wiring repairs Ramp or upper playfield removal General tear-downs and troubleshooting Details: Made from tough TPU (abrasion resistant, impact resistant) Works with most Stern, Bally/Williams, JJP, CGC, Spooky, American Pinball, and Data East/Sega games Lightweight and easy to store in a tool bag or drawer Available in multiple colors Includes: One pair (2) TPU playfield stands Color choice available These are something you’ll use every time you open a game once you have them. Clean, simple, and designed to protect your machines while making work easier.

ads.author: Rob Schoonmaker
ads.title: Gate Of Doom 1990 Full Size Stand Up Arcade Game
ads.description: Gate of Doom, known in Japan as Dark Seal (ダークシール), is a hack 'n slash game developed by Data East and released in 1990 for arcades. Gate of Doom is a hack 'n slash game which uses a top-down, isometric perspective. Players can choose between four different characters, each with their own characteristics and abilities. The player can move and attack in eight directions, as well as unleash a powerful spell once its accumulated enough magic power. Much like in Karnov, the player can pick between available spells by tapping the joystick left and right. Levels are filled with enemies and traps, as well as treasure chests which the player can open to obtain various items and power-ups which give passive boosts to the character.

ads.author: Glenn Musto
ads.title: Atari Tempest Arcade Machine – 1981 Classic Reproduction, w/ modern electronics
ads.description: Modern Re-Creation of the Legendary 1981 Atari Tempest Step back into the golden age of arcades—without the headaches of vintage hardware. This is a brand-new machine built in the style of the iconic Atari Tempest, faithfully recreating the sights, sounds, and gameplay of the original classic. Authentic Gameplay As a Tempest champion in the 1980s and owner of an original machine, I can personally vouch that the gameplay here is spot-on, indistinguishable from a brand-new Tempest as it played in arcades back in the day. Why This Machine Is Better The truth is, the original Tempest was a maintenance nightmare. Its color X-Y CRT monitor burned itself out, circuit boards constantly failed, and many machines ended up in the dump. That’s why working originals are nearly impossible to find—and even if you do, you’re stuck battling those same issues. This machine eliminates every one of those problems, while giving you more: 24" LCD with LED backlighting (IPS panel, any-angle viewing — no fragile CRT). New spinner with dual sealed bearings for silky-smooth precision control. 50-watt stereo sound system with subwoofer, volume control pod, and headphone jack (not just old mono sound). Commercial-grade power: 500+ watt ATX supply plus built-in 1,000-joule surge protector with EMI/RFI filtering. Universal JAMMA harness for plug-and-play swap of other JAMMA boards. Durable build: 3⁄4” commercial-grade cabinet, stainless steel control panel hardware, polycarbonate overlay and graphics (not scratch-prone vinyl). LED marquee lighting (no hot fluorescent bulbs). Poly wheels that roll without scratching floors. Freeplay setup for home use (no quarters required). Choice of keyed vault-style lock or thumb lock for the front door. Extra Features Tempest & Tempest Tubes — play classic levels and unlock options never before accessible. Levels 1 through 99 — explore stages you may have never reached in the arcade. Demonstration Mode: blast through tubes, clear spikes, or jump levels instantly—perfect for testing all 99 levels, whether you’re a pro or a newcomer. Why It Matters This is not just another retro cabinet with emulation slapped inside. It’s a commercial-grade, modernized Tempest machine built to last a lifetime, with gameplay so accurate that arcade veterans can’t tell the difference. Full instructions come with order, including game options, settings, default settings, etc. Defaults are: Game difficulty is Medium, Bonus Life awarded at 20,000 points, and 3 lives per game. Local pickup or buyer arranged packing and shipping. Game is located in Saint Petersburg Florida. If you want it shipped, I will make it available any time at my home for your freight company to pick it up. You must make all arrangements. Size at control panel - approx. 25" wide x 33" deep. Heigth - approx. 73" cabinet top to floor with wheels. Weight - approx. only 170 lbs. (thanks to the LCD/LED monitor). Palleted shipping weight - approx. 210 lbs.

ads.title: Working World Series The Season Arcade Game
ads.description: Relive the Golden Age of Arcades For anyone who remembers the 1980s — when arcades were loud, quarters were precious, and bragging rights lasted all summer — this one hits home. I’m selling my fully functional World Series: The Season arcade game, a true throwback to the era when gameplay mattered more than graphics cards. ads.author: Nick Mizgala
ads.title: Rebuilt Vintage 1990 Neo-Geo Metal Slug Arcade Cabinet $900
ads.description: Up for sale is a 1990 SNK Neo Geo MV-1, 1 slot board in a Dynamo cabinet, with stereo sound and LED credit indicators. The cabinet was rebuilt and repainted in 2017, with new vinyl and t-molding installed. The marquee bracket, coin doors and coin bucket holder were also repainted. The only vinyl that is still original is the control panel, but plexiglass cover was replaced. The coin mechanisms are complete and functional, with matching locks for both coin doors, as well as the back cabinet door. It has a 19" Sharp Image CRT monitor with a beautiful and sharp (no pun intended) picture. It currently has 2" locking casters installed for ease of movement. It currently has a Metal Slug cartridge installed, as the 161 in 1 multi-cart started to flake out. It is included with the sale. It plays well and has been stable, having been taken to Momo Con, Furry Weekend Atlanta and Southern-Fried Gaming Expo a few times over the years. Given the age of this game, it is sold not DOA (Dead on Arrival), but otherwise as-is. It is local pickup only from Tucker, Georgia. Sale is starting at $900, with payment by cash or PayPal. More pictures of the game and the rebuild are available here: https://playeronearcadeservices.com/for-sale/neo-geo-rebuild/

ads.author: Brian Griffin
ads.title: FOUR MILLION BC BALLY 1971
ads.description: Four Million B.C. Pinball Machine by Bally The dinosaur themed classic, Four Million B.C. was a ground breaking 4 player pinball machine for its time. Released by Bally in 1971, Four Million B.C. was designed by Ted Zale (inventor of the zipper flipper feature) with artwork by Dick White. The game features a host of innovative features for an early 1970’s pinball machine including: 3 ball multiball Skill shot ramp (perfect shot lights all three bumpers and scores 3,000 points) Zipper Flippers Volcano hole traps ball and scores 1,000-5,000 points Tar Pit traps ball Left kick back lane when lit (saves the ball from draining) Ball save gate (returns ball to shooter) awards extra ball 3 pop bumpers Two mushroom bumpers release trapped balls Additional features of Four Million B.C. include: 2 Zipper flippers, 3 Pop bumpers, 2 mushroom bumpers, 2 Slingshots, 2 Standup targets, 1 Kick-out hole, Multiball, Ball advance lane, Left outlane kicker, Ramp, Skill shot, Ball return gate, The kick-out hole has a motorized Flash Bonus for variable awards. Maximum displayed point score is 99,990 points per player. Replay wheel maximum: 25. Sound: 1 bell, knocker. This is a super clean game that is is perfect working order. Will not ship COMES WITH 300.00 custom cover
